               <history>
                  <origin>?Lucknow<origDate calendar="#Gregorian">Undated (c.1770)</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>The marks of ownership and sale appear to correspond to those found in other manuscripts formerly belonging to<persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/49590078">Samuel Guise (1751-1811)</persName>, most of which went to the Bland collection via<persName>Samuel Hawtayne Lewin (d 1840)</persName>and<persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/92189357">John Haddon Hindley (1765-1827)</persName>. See<bibl>Ursula Sims-Williams, 'The Strange Story of Samuel Guise: An 18th-Century Collection of Zoroastrian Manuscripts',<title>Bulletin of the Asia Institute</title>, New Series, Vol. 19, (2005), pp. 199-209.</bibl>
                     </p>
                     <p>
                        <bibl>Item 4452 in<title>A supplement to Howell and Stewart’s Catalogue of Oriental and Oriento-Biblical Literature for 1827</title>
                        </bibl>, priced £3 3s.</p>
                     <p>
                        <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/315945284">John Wilks (d 1854)</persName>. Lot 2657 in the 1847 sale, where it was sold to Bohn for £1 1s. See<bibl>Sotheby,<title>Catalogue of the valuable library of an eminent collector [John Wilks]... March 12th, 1847, and ten following days</title>
                        </bibl>and<ref target="https://sdbm.library.upenn.edu/entries/98926">Schoenberg SDBM_98926</ref>.</p>
                     <p>Formerly part of the collection of the Persian scholar<persName type="standard"
                                  ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>. Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in 1866 to<persName type="standard"
                                  ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Purchased by Mrs Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands Library, in<date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date>from<persName type="standard"
                                  ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
